title: Skydiver dies in York after parachute fails to open
text:
Skydiver dies in York after 'canopy entanglement' at national championships, event put on hold Updated March 23, 2017 21:45:32 
A competitor in the Australian National Skydiving Championships has died after his parachute became entangled with another during a formation jump and he collided with a fellow jumper, organisers say. 
Skydive Australia said the man was an experienced skydiver aged in his 30s. 
He was taking part in a formation jump at Skydive York, about 100 kilometres east of Perth, when the accident happened about 5:00pm. 
"It's believed there was a canopy entanglement during a formation jump and the victim collided with another jumper," Skydive Australia said in a statement. 
"No other person was injured in the incident." 
St John's Ambulance said paramedics were called just after 5:00pm and told a man "had hit the ground hard as his parachute did not deploy correctly". 
The RAC rescue helicopter and an ambulance were sent to the scene. 
Police also confirmed they responded to an incident at Spencers Brook Road in Burges. 
The skydiving championships have been put on hold and a meeting of the more than 200 competitors will be held to decide what to do next. 
Police said an investigation was underway and a report would be prepared for the coroner.
